Christian martyr of Cordova."]},{"name":"Saenz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Raul, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Mario, Francisco, Pedro, Ricardo, Alfredo.","Spanish (<b>Sáenz</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sanz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Ricardo, Juan, Luis, Enrique, Jaime, Armando, Ernesto, Francisco, Manuel, Miguel.","German: from a short form, <i>Sando</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>sand</i> ‘true’.","German: habitational name from a place called Sanz in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Navarra","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Edgardo, Guido, Santo, Vito, Angelo, Annamarie, Antonio, Benedicto, Camillo, Dante, Emilio, Fausto, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Mario, Romulo, Sergio.  Spanish Agustin, Herlinda, Manuel, Solita.","Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from Navarre (Castilian <i>Navarra</i>, Basque <i>Nafarroa</i>, French <i>Navarre</i>), a largely Basque-speaking region now divided between Spain and France, but in the Middle Ages an independent Basque kingdom. The name of the region derives from Basque <i>naba</i> ‘plain next to mountains’. Compare   Navarre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Navarrete","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Pedro, Raul, Luis, Miguel, Roberto, Salvador, Francisco.","Spanish: habitational name from any of the places in La Rioja, Aragon, and the Basque Country named in Castilian Navarrete and in Basque Nafarrate (the latter in Araba/Álava province), of Basque origin (compare   Navarra   and   Nafarrate  ).","Basque: Castilianized form of   Nafarrate   or <b>Nafarrete</b>, cognates of 1."]},{"name":"Navarro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Luis, Ramon, Francisco, Miguel, Rafael, Jorge, Pedro.","Spanish, Italian, and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Navarre (see   Navarra  )."]},{"name":"Nava","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Carlos, Luis, Pedro, Manuel, Alfredo, Francisco, Ruben, Javier, Enrique.","Spanish, Catalan, and Asturian-Leonese: habitational name from any of numerous places called Nava, named with <i>nava</i> ‘treeless plateau’, a word of pre-Roman origin, most probably from Basque <i>naba</i> ‘plain next to mountains’ (see   Navarra  )."]},{"name":"Navarre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Jacques, Anatole, Angelle, Camille, Marcelle.","French: habitational name from Navarre (see   Navarra  )."]}]},{"name":"Estefania","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Stephen</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephen","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Estefania Sanchez de Navarra was born in 1070, her father, Sancho